---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Four questions about Sweden, eight parties' answers"
  description="A data-driven look at the Swedish Riksdag 2022-2026, reading roll-call votes, reservations, speeches and the 2022 party manifestos as evidence about what parties see, want, propose and value."
>
  <article class="container">
    <header class="article-hero">
      <p class="byline">Sveriges riksdag 2022-2026 · A data-driven analysis</p>
      <h1>Four questions about Sweden, eight parties' answers</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Politics is usually described in slogans. This is an attempt to
        describe it in data: two and a half thousand chamber votes,
        eleven thousand written reservations, fifty thousand speeches,
        and the eight 2022 party manifestos, read as evidence rather
        than rhetoric.
      </p>
    </header>

    <p>
      When voters compare parties they tend to focus on one thing:
      positions. Where does each party stand on tax, defence, migration,
      health care? It is a thin comparison. Behind every position a
      party has answered, sometimes without saying so out loud, four
      prior questions:
    </p>

    <ol class="four-questions">
      <li><strong>What is wrong with Sweden today?</strong></li>
      <li><strong>What should Sweden be?</strong></li>
      <li><strong>By what means do we get from here to there?</strong></li>
      <li><strong>And what values rank highest when those means
        conflict?</strong></li>
    </ol>

    <p>
      Two parties can agree on a position and disagree on all four
      prior questions. They can share a diagnosis and propose opposite
      mechanisms. They can want the same end state and reach for it
      from opposite values. The richer comparison sits at this lower
      level, and it is also the level at which it becomes possible to
      check whether a party's stated reasoning matches the reasoning it
      actually puts on the parliamentary record.
    </p>

    <p>
      We have eight 2022 manifestos and the full record of the
      2022-2026 mandate. We can read both as text and as behaviour, and
      hold them against one another.
    </p>

    <h2>The shape of the chamber</h2>

    <p>
      Before the four questions, a single orienting picture. Every
      chamber vote in the mandate, member by member, projected into two
      dimensions by PCA on the 349-by-2,501 vote matrix.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/01_behavioural_map.png`} alt="Behavioural map of the Riksdag based on voting patterns, 2022-2026" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        The Riksdag 2022-2026, projected into two dimensions via PCA on
        the voting matrix. The first axis (PC1, 46 % of variance)
        separates the Tidö government bloc from the opposition. The
        second (PC2, 13.5 %) splits the opposition into a
        Socialdemokrat arm and a V/MP/C arm. Centerpartiet sits at the
        centre of the first axis but well down on the second:
        geographically centrist, behaviourally close to the soft left.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The pattern is familiar from American roll-call research but has
      not, as far as we know, been visualised this directly for Swedish
      conditions. What is worth noting is what is <em>not</em> there:
      no third bloc, no coalition cutting across the cabinet/opposition
      line, no realignment from Centerpartiet. Just two clusters and a
      background structure in which V, MP and C sit tightly packed even
      though they officially belong to different ideological traditions.
    </p>

    <p>
      The map collapses every vote in the mandate to one point per party.
      It is structure, not substance. To see where the disagreement actually
      lives, the same matrix split by topic:
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/33_per_topic_stance.png`} alt="Vote stance per party per topic, top 20 by cross-party variance" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Mean vote stance per (party, topic). +1 = the party consistently
        voted Yes on points classified into that topic, -1 = consistently
        No, 0 = mixed. Topics are sorted left-to-right by cross-party
        variance, so the most polarising appear first.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The most polarising topics in the 2022-2026 mandate are migration,
      international aid, pharmaceuticals and dental care, climate, schools
      and municipal services. Migration is the single most differentiating
      topic by some distance. Both the size of the cross-party gap and the
      cluster pattern (V, MP and C on one side; M, KD, L, SD on the other,
      with S in between) repeats with minor variations across these top
      issues. Health, climate and migration draw the same coalition
      structure that the PCA showed in two dimensions; the per-topic view
      simply shows that this structure is consistent across substantively
      different questions.
    </p>

    <p>
      With the orienting picture in place: the four questions, one at a
      time.
    </p>

    <h2>1. What is wrong with Sweden?</h2>

    <p>
      Manifestos are not symmetrical between critique and prescription.
      Some parties spend most of their pages describing the problem.
      Some skip past it almost entirely. We classified each sentence in
      the eight 2022 manifestos into one of four labels (diagnosis, end
      state, mechanism, or other) using a keyword classifier that
      detects the linguistic register of each.
    </p>

    <p>
      Two parties are notably diagnosis-heavy:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Sverigedemokraterna.</strong> 12.8 % of substantive
        sentences are problem statements, by some distance the largest
        share of the eight. They diagnose crime, migration costs, and
        cultural fragmentation.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Kristdemokraterna.</strong> 10.9 % of substantive
        sentences are diagnostic, despite the shortest manifesto of the
        eight (1.6k words total). Per word, KD is the most concerned
        with What Is Wrong. They diagnose family fragility, mental
        health, and weakened community.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      At the other end, Centerpartiet is the most forward-looking
      (4.7 % diagnosis): a manifesto light on critique, heavy on policy
      detail. Vänsterpartiet diagnoses inequality and exploitation
      (9.9 %); Moderaterna diagnoses weak state institutions and the
      lack of consequences (7.5 %).
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/23_manifesto_sim_diagnosis.png`} alt="Diagnosis similarity matrix" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Cosine similarity between the party-level mean embedding of all
        diagnosis sentences. SD and KD share the language of crisis
        most strongly. V and MP cluster on inequality and climate
        framing. The cabinet trio (M, KD, L) does not cluster on
        diagnosis as cleanly as it does on the vote record, because
        the three parties describe different problems even when they
        end up voting for the same solutions.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      One pattern worth flagging: SD's diagnostic vocabulary is closer
      to M's than M's is to L's. The two cabinet allies of M (KD and L)
      diverge from each other on what they say is wrong, while SD and M
      converge. We will return to this when we look at parliamentary
      behaviour.
    </p>

    <h2>2. What should Sweden be?</h2>

    <p>
      End-state sentences are the aspirational core of a manifesto: "we
      want a Sweden where ...", "every child should ...", "a society in
      which ...". The shares differ by almost a factor of six between
      the most and least vision-heavy manifestos.
    </p>

    <table class="data-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Party</th><th>End-state share</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>MP</td><td>17.0 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>C</td><td>10.5 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>L</td><td>10.4 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>V</td><td>7.9 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>S</td><td>7.5 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>M</td><td>6.2 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>SD</td><td>5.7 %</td></tr>
        <tr><td>KD</td><td>3.1 %</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>
      Miljöpartiet is unusually structured around vision: nearly one in
      five sentences describes a future to aspire to. KD is the
      opposite, a short manifesto built almost entirely from critique
      with very thin description of what they want instead. SD lands
      near the bottom too, which fits the diagnosis-heavy reading: a
      manifesto more invested in naming what has gone wrong than in
      describing what should replace it.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/23_manifesto_sim_end_state.png`} alt="End-state similarity matrix" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        End-state language similarity. The pattern flattens. Most
        parties land at 0.78 to 0.90 with one another. The aspirational
        vocabulary of Swedish politics ("trygghet för alla", "ett
        starkt Sverige", "en hållbar framtid") is broadly shared, even
        between parties who agree on almost nothing else.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      A useful read of this matrix is what it implies for voters:
      end-state similarity is a poor discriminator. If two manifestos
      describe the future Sweden they want in similar words, that says
      very little about whether they propose to get there in similar
      ways. End states converge; mechanisms split.
    </p>

    <h2>3. By what means do we get there?</h2>

    <p>
      Mechanism is the most concrete and most differentiated question.
      Moderaterna's manifesto is the most mechanism-heavy of the eight
      (20.5 % of substantive sentences): a fifth of its content is
      proposals using verbs like <em>höja</em>, <em>skärpa</em>,
      <em>reformera</em>, <em>införa</em>. The cabinet's policy
      register is built into the manifesto.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/23_manifesto_sim_mechanism.png`} alt="Mechanism similarity matrix" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Mechanism-language similarity. M, KD and L cluster as expected,
        the cabinet's shared register. C and L cluster slightly
        separately, with a tilt toward market vocabulary. SD sits
        somewhat apart from M, KD, L despite voting almost identically
        with them on the floor.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The cabinet trio and SD vote identically but describe their
      mechanisms in different vocabulary. M, KD and L use
      administrative-procedural language (<em>reformera</em>,
      <em>tilldela</em>, <em>tillsyn</em>). SD uses outcome language
      (<em>Sverige måste</em>, <em>det räcker nu</em>, <em>vi ska
      vända utvecklingen</em>). Their proposals do the same thing.
      Their manifestos describe them differently.
    </p>

    <p>
      The asymmetry continues in parliament. Across the entire mandate
      SD has filed <strong>zero</strong> co-signed reservations with
      any cabinet party. They vote with the cabinet on 98 % of chamber
      votes but they do not put their name to any joint alternative
      proposal. The cabinet parties co-sign more than a hundred
      reservations among themselves. SD votes alongside; it does not
      co-author.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/30_temporal_coauthorship.png`} alt="Reservation co-authorship over the mandate" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        <strong>Left.</strong> Opposition parties co-sign reservations
        with each other continuously, with V-MP the tightest pair (0.30
        to 0.38). All three pairs tick up in 2025/26, the election year,
        as opposition activity intensifies.
        <strong>Right.</strong> SD with the three cabinet parties:
        co-authorship is structurally zero for the first three years.
        In the election year a single uptick: KD-SD rises to 0.24,
        while M-SD and L-SD remain flat. The first co-signed
        reservations between SD and a cabinet party appear only when
        the election is six months away.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Mechanism preferences are not only about who signs with whom. They
      are also about the vocabulary used to describe what should be done.
      Four mechanism dimensions, each with a short curated word list:
      market versus regulation, prevention versus punishment, central
      state versus local, universal versus targeted welfare. Each chamber
      speech is scored on each axis from the relative frequency of the
      two vocabularies.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/29_temporal_how_lexicon.png`} alt="Mechanism vocabulary per party over four parliamentary years" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Four mechanism axes, per party, per parliamentary year. Each
        line is one party's relative frequency of the two vocabularies
        on that axis.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Two patterns stand out:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>The prevention-punishment axis swung sharply.</strong>
        Centerpartiet and Miljöpartiet both moved 0.28 to 0.30 units
        toward punishment vocabulary across the mandate. These are the
        two parties one might least expect to shift in this direction.
        The Tidö parties, who already used more punishment vocabulary
        at the start, moved much less. The opposition adopted the
        framing.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Moderaterna's market vocabulary grew (+0.16) while
        Liberalerna's shrank (-0.11).</strong> The cabinet's two
        ostensibly market-friendly parties moved in opposite
        directions on the market-regulation axis. M's market register
        rose; L's fell as L's chamber speech took on more
        administrative vocabulary.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      The four mechanism dimensions are deliberately small and explicit;
      the word lists are open in the code. The point is not the
      individual word counts but the directional drift across the
      mandate.
    </p>

    <h2>4. The values behind the answers</h2>

    <p>
      Each manifesto invokes a recognisable set of values. Some are
      widely shared (frihet, demokrati). Others belong distinctively
      to one or two parties.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/22_manifesto_values.png`} alt="Value frequency heatmap" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Per-1000-word frequency of value vocabulary across the eight
        2022 manifestos, z-scored across parties. Red = invokes that
        value more than average; blue = less. Values are sorted
        left-to-right by how distinctively one party owns them.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The signature values come through cleanly:
    </p>

    <ul class="signature-values">
      <li><strong>M</strong> · ordning (+2.2 σ). No other value
        distinguishes M as strongly. The Moderate manifesto is built
        around the lack-of-order diagnosis.</li>
      <li><strong>KD</strong> · trygghet (+2.1 σ), ansvar (+1.6 σ),
        staten (+1.4 σ). A statist-conservative cluster, the most
        distinct of all eight.</li>
      <li><strong>C</strong> · jämställdhet (+2.0 σ), marknaden
        (+1.8 σ), individens (+1.6 σ). Liberal in the European sense,
        wholly different from KD despite sitting in the same camp.</li>
      <li><strong>MP</strong> · rättvisa (+2.0 σ), klimat (+1.9 σ),
        solidaritet (+1.2 σ). MP and V share a value vocabulary; on
        climate, MP stands alone.</li>
      <li><strong>L</strong> · frihet (+1.7 σ), valfrihet (+1.7 σ),
        demokrati (+1.6 σ). Classical liberal, value-vocabulary closer
        to C than to KD even though L sits in the cabinet with KD.</li>
      <li><strong>SD</strong> · nationell identitet (+1.8 σ),
        tradition (+1.4 σ), staten (+1.2 σ). The most predictable
        profile in the table.</li>
      <li><strong>V</strong> · jämlikhet (+1.7 σ), solidaritet (+1.6 σ),
        kollektivets (+1.5 σ). Class-based vocabulary, also
        predictable.</li>
      <li><strong>S</strong> · tradition (+1.8 σ), öppenhet (+1.6 σ),
        kollektivets (+1.6 σ). The surprise of the table.
        Socialdemokraterna invoke "tradition" more frequently per word
        than SD does. The vocabulary of the folkhem reads as
        traditional when measured.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      The pairings make sense. V and S share the kollektivets register.
      C and L share the marknaden / valfrihet register. SD and KD share
      the trygghet / staten / tradition register. MP stands alone on
      klimat. The hardest party to summarise in a single value is M,
      whose value vocabulary is sparse compared to the others. Its
      manifesto reads as mechanism-first, value-second.
    </p>

    <h2>Stated and revealed: manifestos against the record</h2>

    <p>
      A manifesto is what a party wants you to think. Parliamentary
      behaviour is what a party does on the record. If the two diverge,
      the manifesto loses some of its predictive value.
    </p>

    <p>
      To measure this, we embedded each manifesto sentence into the
      same vector space as the party's reservation reasoning during
      the mandate, assigned each sentence to one of 28 policy topics
      via cosine similarity, and compared within-topic-within-party
      cells (≥5 manifesto sentences per cell). Without the topic
      restriction the comparison would mostly measure register
      differences (cabinet parties write polished committee
      formulations; opposition parties write technical reservations).
      The topic restriction removes most of that confound.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/26_topic_matched_gap.png`} alt="Topic-matched stated-vs-revealed gap per party" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Per-party mean cosine between manifesto and reservation
        language across covered topics, with the number of comparable
        topics in parentheses. Higher = the party speaks more
        similarly in its manifesto as in its parliamentary work.
        KD (n=1) and MP (n=3) have too few topics with sufficient
        manifesto material to interpret reliably; their bars are
        shown but should be read with caution.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The headline pattern, with the small-sample parties set aside:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>L is the most consistent</strong> (0.76 mean across
        9 topics). Their manifesto language and their reservation
        language describe policy in the same register.</li>
      <li><strong>V has the largest gap</strong> (0.61 across 11
        topics). Their manifesto is aspirational and rhetorical;
        their reservations are technical legal critiques. The
        within-topic gap is real and structural, not a sample
        artefact.</li>
      <li><strong>SD is unexpectedly consistent</strong> (0.71 across
        19 topics). A long, technical manifesto and a long track
        record of detailed reservation work, written in compatible
        registers, until the election year.</li>
    </ul>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/27_party_topic_gap_matrix.png`} alt="Party by topic gap matrix" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        One cell per (party, topic). Pale cells = the party speaks
        similarly in its manifesto and in its parliamentary work on
        that topic; dark cells = the two diverge. Topics are sorted by
        mean divergence across parties.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The topics that diverge most across parties are civil emergency
      preparedness, industrial policy and health care. The pattern is
      the same in each case: manifestos describe these as questions of
      resilience, growth and dignity, while reservations describe them
      as specific clauses, allocations and amendments. The topics where
      the gap is smallest are the ones where manifestos already wrote
      in policy-instrument language: tax (where manifestos already
      state specific rates), defence (where everyone uses Nato
      procurement vocabulary), and migration.
    </p>

    <h3>Two registers inside parliament</h3>

    <p>
      Manifesto is one register. Parliament has two of its own: the
      chamber speech, oral and often delivered without notes, and the
      written reservation, drafted by party staff and polished. If a
      party speaks the same way in both, its parliamentary register is
      internally consistent. If the two diverge, the chamber persona and
      the committee persona differ.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/32_speech_vs_reservation.png`} alt="Per-party speech vs reservation cosine similarity" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Per-party mean speech reasoning vector against mean reservation
        reasoning vector, restricted to (party, topic) cells covered by
        both. Higher = the party uses the same vocabulary in chamber
        speeches as in written reservations.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The four opposition parties and Sverigedemokraterna all land in a
      tight 0.87 to 0.89 band. Inside parliament, each of these five
      parties speaks the same way regardless of register. The cabinet
      bars are hatched because the cabinet writes almost no reservations:
      L has reservation material in only 8 topic cells, KD in 11, M in
      8. The bars are technically computable but the sample is too small
      to read as a finding.
    </p>

    <p>
      What is striking is the opposition's internal consistency. The
      earlier finding (Vänsterpartiet had the largest
      manifesto-versus-reservation gap) is not because V is
      register-inconsistent inside parliament: it is because V's
      manifesto reads in a different register than V's parliamentary
      work, while V's parliamentary work is internally consistent across
      speech and writing. The drift is between manifesto and parliament,
      not within parliament.
    </p>

    <h2>The bloc collapse</h2>

    <p>
      The largest divergence between stated and revealed is not at the
      party level but at the bloc level, and it tells the most
      important story in the mandate.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/07_tido_collapse.png`} alt="The Tidö bloc collapsing into a single cluster" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        The four parties of the Tidö bloc (M, KD, L and SD as a
        support party), per parliamentary year. The mean pairwise
        distance between their centroids falls from 9.08 in 2022/23
        to 0.43 in 2025/26. By the election year the four points sit
        on top of one another.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The technical reading is that the bloc votes increasingly alike.
      The simpler reading, because the cabinet trio has always voted
      as a unit by definition, is that SD has moved toward the
      cabinet's positions, not the other way around. And the movement
      has accelerated.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/08_agreement_trend.png`} alt="Tidö bloc agreement trend over the mandate" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        <strong>Left panel.</strong> Share of chamber votes where the
        entire Tidö bloc voted unanimously. The share rose from 73 %
        in 2024/25 to 98 % in 2025/26, in step with the start of the
        election year.
        <strong>Right panel.</strong> The rise is driven entirely by
        SD aligning with the cabinet's positions, not the cabinet
        adjusting toward SD.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Of the 687 chamber votes in 2025/26, SD deviated from the
      cabinet in eleven. In the same year SD's filed reservations fell
      from 574 (2024/25) to 17.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/21_sd_reservation_collapse.png`} alt="SD reservations per parliamentary year, the election-year collapse" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Reservations filed per party and parliamentary year. The thick
        yellow line is SD: 749, 402, 574, 17. The opposition parties
        rise or hold steady. The cabinet parties (M, KD, L) are
        excluded as, being the majority, they file very few.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      A reservation is the written record of a party's alternative
      position. In a single year SD went from producing more such
      records than the rest of the opposition combined to producing
      essentially none. The party of opposition stopped opposing on
      the record, one year before an election.
    </p>

    <p>
      The mechanism comparison from the manifesto section returns
      here. M and SD voted alike during the mandate, and M's
      reservation-text register drifted measurably toward SD's across
      the same period. The boundary between cabinet and support party
      has thinned from both sides: SD moving into the cabinet's
      positions, M moving into SD's vocabulary. By the election year
      they are, on the parliamentary record, one entity.
    </p>

    <h3>The collapse against the wider picture</h3>

    <p>
      The Tidö story is dramatic but it is not the only movement in the
      mandate. The same Procrustes-aligned PCA, run year by year, traces
      where every party drifted.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/28_centroid_trajectories.png`} alt="Each party's voting centroid drift across four parliamentary years" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Each party's voting centroid across the four parliamentary
        years of the mandate. Dot size grows with year. Lines show the
        trajectory; the arrow on the last segment points to where the
        party landed in the election year.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Three movements stand out beyond the Tidö collapse:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Miljöpartiet moved up on PC2 the most</strong>, from
        below the axis to well above it. The within-bloc structure
        captured by PC2 changed meaning for MP across the mandate. By
        2025/26 they sit closer to the C-MP axis than to V.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Vänsterpartiet moved toward the centre on PC1</strong>,
        from -8 in 2022/23 to roughly -2 in 2025/26. Their position
        opposite the cabinet softened on the vote axis even as their
        reservation activity stayed high.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Socialdemokraterna barely moved at all.</strong> The
        largest opposition party is the most stationary point on the
        map.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      The bloc fusion shows up at the individual level too. Compute, for
      each MP, the ratio of their distance to their own party's centroid
      against their distance to the nearest other party. A ratio above 1
      means the MP votes more like another party than their own.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/31_defectors.png`} alt="Top behavioural defectors over the mandate" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        The 12 MPs with the highest distance-to-own-party / distance-to-nearest-other-party
        ratio, on a log scale. The dashed line marks equidistance. A
        ratio of 5x means the MP is five times further from their own
        party's centroid than from another party's.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Eight of the top twelve defectors are Liberalerna MPs whose
      voting record sits closer to KD or M than to L. The party of
      Bengt Westerberg is structurally split at the individual level:
      a substantial share of the L caucus is behaviourally inside the
      Christian-Democratic or Moderate clusters. The collapse seen at
      party-mean level is not just the cabinet's three colours blending
      into a single centroid. It is also the L party itself thinning
      from within.
    </p>

    <hr />

    <p class="method-note">
      All analysis is based on reproducible methods over public data
      from <a href="https://data.riksdagen.se">data.riksdagen.se</a>
      and the eight 2022 party manifestos from the SND "Vi vill"
      archive. Source code and full method write-up at
      <a href="https://github.com/freol35241/ps-sverige">GitHub</a>.
      No interviews, no surveys, no subjective judgements beyond
      those needed to define keyword pools, topic clusters and
      vocabulary lists, which are openly documented in the code.
    </p>
  </article>
